    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.48a_0001"/>
                
                <note>[<unclear>March</unclear>, 1958]</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">48a</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>The Deshler Hilton Hotel</figDesc>
                    </figure>
                
                    <hi rend="caps">THE</hi> <hi rend="italics">Deshler Hilton</hi> <hi rend="caps">COLUMBUS, O.
                        <lb/>
                    TELEPHONE CA</hi>pital 4-1221    ∙   <hi rend="caps">CONRAD N. HILTON</hi>, President     ∙       <hi rend="caps">TRUETT GORE</hi>, General Manager
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">NOEL W, HARMAN</hi></addrLine>
                        <addrLine>23885 <hi rend="caps">WESTWOOD ROAD</hi></addrLine>
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">WESTLAKE, OHIO</hi></addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihart<sic>Neihardt</sic>:-</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It was a wonderful suprise to hear from you and needless to say &#8212; I was delighted.</p>
                
                <p>My Father is quite ill not with a heart condition and I may have to fly suddenly to Omaha to see him, however, we expect that he will be allright, although he must stop his high-energy office activities.</p>
                
                <p>As you may recall Dad always went after everything in "High <unclear>Gear</unclear>," and maintained his terrific pace all his life. I never could keep up with him, always slow like my English Grandfather. Mother is well though and I know they would appreciate: a line from you.
                    <address>
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">N.K. HARMAN</hi></addrLine>
                        <addrLine>3526 <hi rend="caps">NO</hi> 58 St.</addrLine>
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">OMAHA, NEBR.</hi></addrLine>
                    </address>
                </p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.48a_0002"/>
                
                <p>I am certain that I remember your Daughter Alice and your Son Sigard. I must have been around ten or eleven and you made a number of small paper boats similar to paper hats which we sailed in a tub at the back of the house, 41 years ago &#8212; it seems to be beyond time but what wonderful days those early years were &#8212; I shall never forget them.</p>
                
                <p>I spent several January's in the <unclear>Seorcy</unclear> Area of Arkansas, hunting Quail many years ago and came back up through the White River Country on my return to Omaha. I understood you lived up there at one time but our traveling schedule prevented me from ever looking you up.</p>
                
                <p>My daughter, Mary Kay, is an <unclear>avid</unclear> little rider and only lives to go Horseback riding having several years of <unclear>training</unclear> by professionals. She is <unclear>now</unclear> twelve years old and taking lessons from a Mrs Packer 75 years old, who is <unclear>very</unclear> active and still an excellent Show rider.</p>
                
                <note type="curatorial"><hi rend="caps">JOHN G. NEIHARDT CENTER</hi></note>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
